<br>
 Say there is some big mass of inert matter that is in perfect balance because all of reality and and it's energies have come to rest or have been forever at rest. Would this be pre big bang and would time be nonexistent due to the fact that speed or movement does not yet exist? If so then what would possibly trigger the explosion which would result in our universe and create movement, aka time.<br>
<br>
I'm way out my league here but if you were to reverse the big bang and go back to the instant of singular mass would not all atoms/protons/electrons/neutrons eventually attain the perfect balance and cease all movement? Would time slow as this happened gradually or would this happen in an instant of mathematical perfection thus ending time? Either way, time would seem to have a beginning and an end but to me that is inconceivable. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/uaurianne.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Aurianne</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/black_fire.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Contributing Member</span><br>  Posts: 416<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(2/15/02 9:28 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm24.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=17.topic&index=171>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Somebody should start a religion thread</span><hr size=1> Under general relativity, time slows down as you accelerate, not the other way around.<br>
