<br>
Proof of infinity?  Well Zozz, I would have to say that mathematically you are correct, that it can only be proven within our own mathematical concepts.<br>
<br>
I was going to use the example of travelling half the distance to heaven.  If you travelled half the distance to heaven and stopped.  Then you travelled half the remaining distance to heaven and stopped.  Then travelled half of that remaining distance, etc.  You would, in theory, get very very close to heaven, but you would never get there.  You would always be travelling half the remaining distance required to get there.  As a result, the distance to heaven would get infinitely smaller as the time required to get there would get infinitely longer.  (there is probably a huge flaw in this argument)  Unless of course 3 dimensional travel if fundamentally flawed.  Which brings me to...<br>
<br>
One of the best mathematical books I ever read that gave me an interesting perspective on both the universe and heaven was a small book called Flatlands.  If you haven't read it, I highly recommend it.  It is short (41 pages) and pretty easy to understand even if you are not a mathematician.<br>
<br>
It basically describes life in a 2 dimensional world.  How perspective comes into play.  If you are in a flat world, how you can't go over or under anything you have to go around it, etc.  As the book progresses, you get accustomed to the rules of this two dimensional world and realize the complete brainfuck that happens when you realize that the third dimension watching this world is completely inconceivable to those within the 2 dimensional world.<br>
<br>
It also covers the mathematical progression of dimensions.  For example:<br>
<br>
1 point - dot<br>
2 points - line<br>
4 points - square (2 dimensional representation)<br>
8 points - cube (same square in three dimensions)<br>
<br>
Then imagine that same square in 4 dimensions.  It would have 16 points. (perhaps)  Smoke some dope, try to get your mind around it.  It hurts.<br>
<br>
Just as the people of flatland could have no concept of that which was above or below them, we have no concept of that which exists (the equivalent of above or below) in the next dimension.<br>
<br>
So in that regard, god (or whomever) could be standing right beside you (from his perspective) and you would never see him.  Or even moreso, he could be beside you and all around you at the same time.  Or by travelling half the distance to heaven, you actually passed right through it. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
It is early, first cup of coffee, so I hope this made sense.<br>
<br>
Also, on the topic of working within known systems, i think it was Rene Descartes who said that you would never dream of a color that was not a product of colors you had already seen.<br>
<br>
Ahliana Ochsanfree<br>
